  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "If a truck is hauling 1000 pounds of parakeets that are all sitting on their perch does it get 1000 pounds lighter if they all fly at the same time?",
  "response": "No, the truck does not get 1000 pounds lighter if all the parakeets fly at the same time. \n\nThe weight of the parakeets on the truck is due to the force of gravity acting on them. When the parakeets take off and fly, they are no longer in contact with the truck, but the truck's weight remains the same. The parakeets' flight does not change the mass of the truck itself.\n\nHowever, there might be a very brief moment during takeoff where the parakeets are pushing against their perches to launch themselves into the air. During this brief moment, the truck might experience a very slight reduction in the total downward force due to the parakeets pushing off. But once the parakeets are airborne, the total weight of the truck and everything still on it returns to what it was before the parakeets took off, minus the weight of the parakeets themselves.\n\nSo, the truck would feel 1000 pounds lighter only after the parakeets have left the truck completely, not while they are in the process of flying away.",
